Another feature of this birth, which is found alike in Virgil and Isaiah, is that it is irn- mediately impending. According to Virgil it is to take place in this very year, the year of Pollio’s consulship; according to Isaiah vii. 14 the child is shortly to be born; in ix. 6 he is already born; in vii. 16 and viii. 4 reference is made to his growing intelligence3 in xi. the glory of his kingdom is described. In both writers the question as to the identity of the child is left in vague- nesS, and is therefore variously answered by interpreters.
